name.treatmentStandardsRoutes: residential heating systems from natural gas, condensing boiler, max. heat output 14,9 kW

dataSetInformation.common:generalComment: A detailed model of a wall-mounted natural gas condensing boiler was used. The data set covers all relevant process steps / technologies over the supply chain of the represented cradle to gate inventory with a good overall data quality.

locationOfOperationSupplyOrProduction.descriptionOfRestrictions: Average data, no individual sub-locations explicitly considered.

technology.technologyDescriptionAndIncludedProcesse: The data set represents the currently used technical standard of newly installed residential heating systems. The heat is produced in a wall-mounted natural gas condensing boiler with a maximum heat output of 14,9 kW, used as residential heating system. As burner, a low NOx-burner is used. The air and natural gas is well mixed before being burned and the air/fuel ratio is intentionally kept high to arrive at low flame temperatures, thus avoiding the creation of thermal NOx. To be able to use the condensing boiler technology, the return temperature of the water to the boiler has to be low. As the exhaust gas is cooled below the dew point, condensation of the water (vapour) contained in the exhaust gas is occurring and the enthalpy of evaporation can thus be additionally used for heating. The condensate is released to the residential sanitation. A blower has to be installed to convey the low temperature exhaust gas up the chimney. The chimney is of a corrosion resistant material, as further condensation is occurring in there. Furthermore the data set comprises the production of the device as well as its end-of-life. The data set considers the whole supply chain from exploration over natural gas processing and preparation to transport to the households. The background system is addressing the use of electricity and natural gas as follows: The European average natural gas consumption mix with its region-specific energy carrier properties (e.g. element and energy content) is accounted for. The electricity used is an average of the electricity used in EU-27 which is derived from the electricity data sets modelled according to the individual country-specific situations. The country-specific modelling is achieved on multiple levels. Firstly the individual power plants in service are modelled according to the current national grid. This includes net losses and imported electricity. Second, the national emission and efficiency standards of the power plants are modelled. Third, the country-specific fuel supply (share of resources used, by import and / or domestic supply) including the country-specific properties (e.g. element and energy contents) are accounted for. Fourth, the import, transport, mining and exploration processes for the energy carrier supply chain are modelled according to the specific situation of each power-producing country. The different mining and exploration techniques (emissions and efficiencies) in the different exploration countries are accounted for according to current engineering knowledge and information. Transports: All relevant and known transport processes used are included. Overseas transports including rail and truck transport to and from major ports for imported bulk resources are included. Furthermore all relevant and known pipeline and / or tanker transport of gases and oil imports are included. Energy carriers: Coal, crude oil, natural gas and uranium are modelled according to the specific import situation (see electricity).
technology.technologicalApplicability: Heat on a temperature level of ca. 55°C at the outlet of the heating system with the purpose of residential heating.

LCIMethodAndAllocation.deviationsFromLCIMethodApproaches: All allocations are used in the upstream processes. For the combined crude oil, natural gas and natural gas liquids production allocation by net calorific value is applied. For the combined heat and power production, allocation by exergetic content is applied. For the electricity generation and by-products, e.g. gypsum, allocation by market value is applied due to no common physical properties.
LCIMethodAndAllocation.modellingConstants: An annual use efficiency of 99% was taken into account for the heating system. The annual use efficiency is the ratio of produced heat to fuel input during one year, with a max. of 111% related to the net calorific value. All data used in the calculation of the LCI results refer to net calorific value. For the transport of energy carriers average transport processes with specific parameter settings e.g. transport distances and route (ship, pipeline, rail, road) are used.

dataSourcesTreatmentAndRepresentativenes.dataCutOffAndCompletenessPrinciples: Cut-off rules for each unit process: Coverage of at least 95 % of mass and energy of the input and output flows, and 98 % of their environmental relevance (according to expert judgement).
dataSourcesTreatmentAndRepresentativenes.deviationsFromCutOffAndCompletenessPrinc: The coverage for the exploration data (crude oil, natural gas, natural gas liquids) is only 90% of mass and energy and 95% of the environmental relevance (expert judgement).
dataSourcesTreatmentAndRepresentativenes.dataSelectionAndCombinationPrinciples: The data sources for the complete product system are sufficiently consistent: The key emissions of the heating system (carbon monoxide, volatile organic compounds, polychlorinated dibenzodioxins, nitrogen oxides, mercury, dust and dinitrogen oxide) are measured values taken from studies. Few other emissions from the heating system are calculated via energy carrier composition in combination with (literature-based) combustion models. The data on the energy carrier supply chain is based on statistics and energy carrier composition, as well as industry and literature data on the inventory of exploration and production. LCI modelling is fully consistent.
dataSourcesTreatmentAndRepresentativenes.dataTreatmentAndExtrapolationsPrinciples: Data measured at a group of representative heating systems have been used to represent the European average. For dust the assumption was made that all the emissions are PM2,5. The measurements are taken from studies conducted in Germany, Austria and Switzerland. The described technology is representative for EU-27. As fuel a representative average for EU-27 has been taken into account.

dataSourcesTreatmentAndRepresentativenes.useAdviceForDataSet: The data set represents the life cycle of the heating system and the cradle to gate inventory of the energy supply. It can be used to characterise the whole supply chain for heat used for residential heating. The data set comprises the inventory up to the outlet of the heating system. It excludes the system components necessary to distribute the heat in the house and eventually to combine it with other heating sources. Combination with individual unit processes using this commodity enables the generation of user-specific (product) LCAs.

review.common:reviewDetails: Inventory: The internal review was done by several iteration steps concerning raw data validation, raw data documentation, representativity, completeness and consistency of modelling with regard to ISO 14040 and 14044.; Documentation: The review of the documentation was performed by Ecobilan and is in compliance with ISO 14040 and 14044. The data set documentation is correct in view of the appropriateness of the information provided. It includes all relevant information in view of data quality and scope of application of the respective LCI result.

common:commissionerAndGoal.intendedApplications: This background LCI data set can be used for any types of LCA studies.

publicationAndOwnership.common:accessRestrictions: The data set can be used free of charge by anybody to perform LCA studies, to distribute it to third parties, to convert it to other formats, to develop own data sets etc. as long as the copyright and license conditions for the ELCD data sets and the ILCD format are met that can be accessed via http://lca.jrc.ec.europa.eu. Please note e.g. that reference must be given to the 'Owner of data set' and to the 'ELCD database' plus version number, when using the data set or parts thereof. Please note also, that any modifications/omissions of the data set results in invalidity of any existing 'Official approval of data set by producer/operator', that the impression must be avoided that this would still be a complete ELCD data set, and that the content of further fields has to be adjusted. For details see the aforementioned copyright and license conditions.
